    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Yordan Alvarez** (75.76) and **Junior Caminero** (73.35) serving as our primary offensive anchors. **Yordan Alvarez** benefits from a massive 14% park factor boost, helping to insulate his production against a L/L matchup disadvantage. Meanwhile, **Junior Caminero** faces a favorable 4.83 xERA from Javier Assad, capitalizing on his high-order placement and strong platoon splits. We are also aggressively deploying **Trea Turner** (70.39) and **Kyle Schwarber** (69.61) against Robbie Ray. Despite the pitcher's talent, the combination of wind blowing out and high-leverage order spots creates a high-ceiling environment for both, though **Trea Turner** will need to contend with a minor efficiency dip due to an elite opposing catcher.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was **Caleb Durbin**, whose 46.02 score narrowly missed our utility cut. While **Caleb Durbin** offers the speed element we covet, the optimizer favored **Kazuma Okamoto** (44.68) and **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (58.81) due to slightly better defensive/platoon situational alignment despite the daunting matchup against Yoshinobu Yamamoto. We also have concerns regarding **Christian Yelich** (42.06); he is teetering on the edge of the \"below floor\" threshold as he faces the elite arm of Garrett Crochet in wind-in conditions. We will monitor his official lineup status closely, as any shift down the order could necessitate a late swap for the fresher legs of **Lars Nootbaar** or **Zac Veen**.\n\nBeyond the bench, we are proceeding with caution regarding **Dillon Dingler** (43.39) and **Kazuma Okamoto** (44.68). Both players carry significant platoon risks today, and with several lineup slots still pending official confirmation, our projected efficiency scores are volatile. **Hyeseong Kim** and **Victor Scott II** remain must-starts for the Zebras due to our emphasis on stolen base scarcity, even though their #9 spots in the lineup suppress their overall daily efficiency scores. We are effectively betting that their baserunning contributions will outweigh the lower run-scoring potential inherent in the bottom of the order.",
